column2: In ancient Korea the power of the bureaucrats often eclipsed that of the central authorities, including the monarch.A complex system of checks and balances prevented any one section of the government from gaining overwhelming power.
The Gongjo Panseo is the minister responsible for industry, public works, manufacturing, mining

The Daesaheon or Inspector General was in charge of running the Office of the Inspector General, part of the Three Offices, a group of organisms responsible for checks and balance on the king and the officials.
The Daesagan or Chief Censor was in charge of running the Office of Censors, part of the Three Offices, a group of organisms responsible for checks and balance on the king and the officials.

The Bujehak or Deputy Chief Scholar was in charge of running the Office of Special Advisors, part of the Three Offices, a group of organisms responsible for checks and balance on the king and the officials.
The Ijo Panseo is the minister responsible with the appointment of officials
The Jwauijeong or Left State Councillor was onde of the highest-ranking officials in the government. The power of State Council was inversely proportional to the king's power.
The Uuijeong or Right State Councillor was onde of the highest-ranking officials in the government. The power of State Council was inversely proportional to the king's power.
The Jwachanseong or Left Minister was onde of the assistent officials in the government. The power of State Council was inversely proportional to the king's power.
Uichangseong or Right Minister was onde of the assistent officials in the government. The power of State Council was inversely proportional to the king's power.
The Jwachamchan or Left Councillor was onde of the assistent officials in the government. The power of State Council was inversely proportional to the king's power.
The Uichamchan or Right Councillor was onde of the assistent officials in the government. The power of State Council was inversely proportional to the king's power.
The Sain was a Lower Concillor official in the government. The power of State Council was inversely proportional to the king's power.
The Geomsang was a Lower Concillor official in the government. The power of State Council was inversely proportional to the king's power.
The Daesaseong was the official in charge of the Seonggyungwan or Royal Academy.
The Doseungji was in charge of the Seungseon or Royal Secretary responsible for dealing with commands of the king
The Juseo were recorders primarily responsible of delivering the monarch's orders to government organizations and to report on official affairs of the state organizations to the throne.
The Paanyoon or Lord Mayor of Hanyang - Present day Seol, was the head official of the Capital Bureau responsible for running the capital.
The Suhaengja is a title of minor legal responsability
Known also as Haedong or Jungdo, Beopseong was a scholastic branch of Buddhism native to Korea that synthesized the seemingly divergent strands of Indian and Chinese Buddhist doctrine.
A scholastic branch of Korean Buddhism that represented the was based on the Indian Yogacara system of thought.
A scholastic branch focused on study and implementation of moral discipline or Buddhist ethics. It derives directly from the Indian Vinaya School
A scholastic branch based in the themes of the Mahaparinirvana-sutra and initially popular in pre-unification Silla.
A scholastic branch which focused on the actualization of the metaphysics of interpenetration as found in the Huayan jing, very popular among the aristocracy.
The Korean meditational school turned towards a meditation-based view of practice which came to be known as chan known in the West through its Japanese variant called Zen.
Shingyo Buddhism boasts several sects. It might be advantageous for us to change our branch.
